        The decision to make information internal or external isn't always black and white. Some content
        starts as internal documentation and evolves into customer-facing resources. Other information
        remains confidential indefinitely. And some knowledge serves dual purposes, requiring careful
        management to ensure the right audiences see appropriate versions. This guide will help you
        navigate these decisions and build a knowledge architecture that serves your entire organization.
      </p>
      <p class="text-black/70 leading-relaxed mt-4">
        As organizations grow, the volume of information they generate grows exponentially. Without clear
        boundaries between internal and external knowledge, chaos ensues. Sensitive information leaks,
        customers encounter incomplete or confusing documentation, and employees waste time searching
        through irrelevant content. A well-designed knowledge architecture prevents these problems by
        creating clear distinctions while maintaining the flexibility to evolve content over time.
      </p>
