          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-black mb-3">Start Internal, Then Externalize</h3>
          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-black/70 leading-relaxed">
            <p>
              Begin by documenting everything internally, even if you think it might eventually become
              external content. This approach provides several advantages. First, it allows you to
              iterate quickly on content without worrying about public scrutiny. Internal stakeholders
              can review and refine documentation before it faces customer eyes. Second, it creates a
              testing ground where you can identify gaps, errors, and unclear explanations that might
              confuse external users.
            </p>
            <p>
              As content matures and proves valuable internally, evaluate whether it would benefit
              customers as well. Documentation that consistently answers internal questions often
              addresses customer needs too. Before externalizing, invest in polishing: remove internal
              jargon, add context for users who lack institutional knowledge, and ensure the content
              represents your brand appropriately. This workflow ensures external content is accurate,
              comprehensive, and professionally presented.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-black mb-3">Maintain Clear Boundaries</h3>
          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-black/70 leading-relaxed">
            <p>
              Avoid the temptation to duplicate content between internal and external systems without
              a clear strategy. While some overlap is natural, wholesale copying creates maintenance
              nightmares. When content exists in both places, you must update it twice, and it's
              inevitable that versions will drift out of sync, leading to confusion and errors.
            </p>
            <p>
              Instead, use linking and referencing. Internal documentation can link to public resources
              for standard features while adding internal context, procedures, and commentary. For
              example, an internal guide might say: "Follow the public setup guide [link], then configure
              these internal-specific settings..." This approach keeps public documentation as the single
              source of truth while allowing internal documentation to build upon it without duplication.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-black mb-3">Cross-Link Strategically</h3>
          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-black/70 leading-relaxed">
