              When content exists in both systems, create intentional connections between them.
              Cross-linking helps users discover related information and understand the relationship
              between internal and external resources. However, be thoughtful about the direction
              of linksâ€”internal systems can link to external resources freely, but external content
              should never link to internal systems (which would create dead links for customers).
            </p>
            <p>
              Consider creating "internal addendum" articles that supplement public documentation
              with internal-specific details. For example, if you have a public API documentation
              page, the internal version might include information about rate limiting for internal
              services, debugging procedures, or contact information for the API team. This layered
              approach keeps public documentation clean while providing internal teams with the
              context they need.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="border-l-4 border-orange-500 pl-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-black mb-3">Governance and Ownership</h3>
          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-black/70 leading-relaxed">
            <p>
              Establish clear ownership for both internal and external knowledge bases. Without
              accountability, documentation quickly becomes stale and unreliable. For internal
              systems, assign subject matter experts as owners for different content areas. These
              owners are responsible for keeping their sections current, reviewing suggestions for
              improvements, and ensuring accuracy.
            </p>
            <p>
              External knowledge bases often benefit from dedicated technical writing teams or
              content strategists who can ensure consistency in voice, style, and quality. However,
              subject matter experts should still be involved in creating and reviewing technical
              content. A collaborative workflow where experts draft content and writers polish it
              often produces the best results. Regular content audits help identify outdated
              information, broken links, and gaps in coverage.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
